<subSubSection pageId="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,639,396,1729]" pageId="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,290,689,710]" pageId="18">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to the first author’ s mother, Amy Owens, whose years of friendship and encouragement have been of immeasurable value and made the current study possible.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,639,396,1729]" pageId="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,279,796,817]" pageId="18">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Externally, the presence of a deep impression on ventrite III with the vertical shelf extending to the apex of ventrite II distinguishes this species from 
<taxonomicName box="[328,462,876,897]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rhexius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="substriatus">
<emphasis box="[328,462,876,897]" italics="true" pageId="18">R. substriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chandler" authorityYear="1990" box="[477,587,876,897]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rhexius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stephani">
<emphasis box="[477,587,876,897]" italics="true" pageId="18">R. stephani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1908" box="[151,282,903,924]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rhexius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis box="[151,282,903,924]" italics="true" pageId="18">R. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Additionally, the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[549,626,903,924]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[175,206,1710,1729]" captionTargetBox="[183,562,991,1674]" captionTargetId="figure-354@12.[151,638,977,1687]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 11. Pseudactium jaitlynum, aedeagus, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339696" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339696/files/figure.png" pageId="18">Fig. 11c</figureCitation>
), bears a ventral lobe with a semicircular, internal fold on the right side, and the median lobe has three distal extensions that distinguish this species from all others in the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
